QUESTION 1. 
In the late 1970s, Dr. Ian Stirling, OC, a former CWS/ECCC scientist and the “Father” of polar bear research, began studying polar bears in Western Hudson Bay. He and colleagues were early adopters of satellite tracking and in 2000 began placing satellite tags on females in Western Hudson Bay. Tags are reliable up to about 1 year, although some go offline before a year is up and cannot be monitored further. For tags that stayed online, based on a mortality switch in the tags, biologists are able to determine whether the animal is alive or dead from the signal type. We have obtained a dataset of tags that were deployed in spring between 2000 and 2017 and were still online 1 year later. We have information on the state of the female one year after deployment (either alive or dead). We also have information on the age of the female at deployment (age 1, subadults; age 2, adults). Finally, we have information on the number of ice free days (standardized) in Hudson Bay during the summer after tag deployment.

REMEMBER TO MAKE AGE INTO A FACTOR IN YOUR DATA!  


```{r, echo = FALSE, results = FALSE}

#SIMULATE DATA
set.seed(6)

#sea ice free days in Hudson Bay, 1979-2010
ice.free <- c(153,173,154,185,153,161,172,172,174,160,171)
ice.new <- sample(ice.free,7)+sample(-10:10,7)
ice <- c(ice.free,ice.new)
ice.std <- ( ice - mean(ice) ) / sd(ice)

b.ice <- -0.8
b.1 <- 2.3
b.2 <- 3.1
b.age <- c(b.1,b.2)

n.bear <- 314
p.data <- matrix(NA,nrow=n.bear,ncol=3)
for(i in 1:n.bear){
  p.data[i,1] <- ice.std[sample(1:length(ice),1)]
  p.data[i,2] <- sample(c(1:2),1)
  p <- 1/(1+exp(-(b.age[p.data[i,2]] + b.ice*p.data[i,1])))
  p.data[i,3] <- rbinom(1,1,p) 
}
PB.data <- as.data.frame(p.data)
colnames(PB.data) <- c("ice","age","survival")
PB.data$age <- as.factor(PB.data$age)

write.csv(PB.data,"PB_data.csv",row.names=FALSE)
rm(list=ls(all = TRUE))

PB.data <- read.csv("PB_data.csv")
PB.data$age <- as.factor(PB.data$age)

```


a.	We suspect that there are effects of ice and of age on annual survival. Build a model that reflects this hypothesis. 

```{r, echo = FALSE, results = FALSE}

smod <- glm(survival ~ age + ice , PB.data, family = "binomial")
summary(smod)
```


b.	Look at binned residual plots and the Hosmer-Lemeshow test. Create halfnormal plots of hatvalues and Cook’s distances. What did you learn?  

```{r, echo = FALSE, results = FALSE, fig.show = 'hide'}

#binned residuals 
binnedplot(fitted(smod),residuals(smod)) 

#hosmer lemeshow - sample size is too small here 
logitgof(PB.data$survival,fitted(smod))

#H-L by hand - try different breaks
#can try different breaks 
eta <- predict(smod,type = "link")
PB.data <- mutate(PB.data, predprob = predict(smod, type = "response"))
gdf <- group_by(PB.data, cut(eta, breaks = unique(quantile(eta,(1:15/16)))))
hldf <- summarise(gdf,y = sum(survival), ppred=mean(predprob), count = n())
hlstat <- with(hldf, sum((y-count*ppred)^2/(count*ppred*(1-ppred))))
1-pchisq(hlstat,nrow(hldf)-1)

#hatvalues
halfnorm(hats <- hatvalues(smod))

#cooks 
halfnorm(cooks <- cooks.distance(smod))
```

c.	What model best describes survival for female polar bears in Hudson Bay? Given your two predictors (age and ice) there are 4 possible models you could build. Build these 4 models. Then provide a table with AIC values, delta AIC values, and model weights. 

```{r, echo = FALSE, results = FALSE}

smod1 <- glm(survival ~ age + ice , PB.data, family = "binomial")
smod2 <- glm(survival ~ age , PB.data, family = "binomial")
smod3 <- glm(survival ~ ice , PB.data, family = "binomial")
smod4 <- glm(survival ~ 1 , PB.data, family = "binomial")

#AIC 
AIC.tab <- data.frame(NA,nrow=4,ncol=4)
AIC.tab [1,2] <- summary(smod1)$deviance + 2*3
AIC.tab [2,2] <- summary(smod2)$deviance + 2*2
AIC.tab [3,2] <- summary(smod3)$deviance + 2*2
AIC.tab [4,2] <- summary(smod4)$deviance + 2*1
AIC.tab [,3] <- AIC.tab[,2] - min(AIC.tab[,2])
AIC.tab [,4] <- exp(-0.5*AIC.tab[,3]) / sum(exp(-0.5*AIC.tab[,3]))
AIC.tab [,1] <- c("age + ice","age","ice","1")
```


d.	Predict expected survival of polar bears as a function of ice availability under your best model (account for other factors, e.g., if age appears in your best model, make predictions for both age groups). Use as your ice values the set of unique ice values from the existing dataset. Make a plot of survival by ice value (include both ages as necessary dependent on the effects in your top model) and provide confidence intervals on the plot.

```{r, echo = FALSE, results = FALSE, fig.show = 'hide'}

icevals <- sort(unique(PB.data$ice))
newData1 <- data.frame(age = c(rep("1",length(icevals)),rep("2",length(icevals))),ice = rep(icevals,2) )
summ.best <- matrix(NA,nrow = nrow(newData1), ncol=3)
boots <- 1000
yest <- matrix(NA,nrow=nrow(newData1),ncol=boots)
for(i in 1:boots){
  y <- unlist(simulate(smod1))
  ymod <- update(smod1,y ~ .)
  yest[,i] <- predict(ymod,newdata = newData1, type="response")
}
for(i in 1:nrow(newData1)){
  summ.best[i,1] <- mean(yest[i,]) 
  summ.best[i,2] <- quantile(yest[i,],probs=0.025) 
  summ.best[i,3] <- quantile(yest[i,],probs=0.975) 
}

ice <- sort(unique(PB.data$ice))

par(mai = c(1,1,0.5,0.5))
plot(ice, summ.best[1:(nrow(newData1)/2),1],type = "l",ylab = "Survival",xlab = "Ice Free Days - Standardized",cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis=1.5,ylim=c(0,1))
lines(ice, summ.best[1:(nrow(newData1)/2),2],lty= 2)
lines(ice, summ.best[1:(nrow(newData1)/2),3],lty= 2)

lines(ice, summ.best[(nrow(newData1)/2+1):nrow(newData1),1],lty= 1,col="red")
lines(ice, summ.best[(nrow(newData1)/2+1):nrow(newData1),2],lty= 2,col="red")
lines(ice, summ.best[(nrow(newData1)/2+1):nrow(newData1),3],lty= 2,col="red")

```
